UNITED STATES (US)
</RE>
<LP>
   Jake Blehm's biggest business problem isn't selling his
product -- it's explaining to baffled customers what exactly
it is they've just bought.
   Mr. Blehm, owner of Buena Bio Systems Inc. in Santa Paula,
Calif., recently mailed nearly 500,000 trichograma wasps to a
client to fight moth larvae, which attack tomatoes and corn.
The wasps, mailed in the form of larvae inside moth eggs,
emerge two or three days later. Buena Bio Systems glues these
grainy eggs to small sheets of heavy paper.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   When the shipment arrived, the bewildered customer called
<PERSON>Mr. Blehm</PERSON>. "He said, `Hey, where are the wasps you were
supposed to send me. All I got are three sheets of
sandpaper,'" says <PERSON>Mr. Blehm</PERSON>. "I told him to find the
instructions and pull out a magnifying glass. He wrote us a
letter later apologizing."
   <PERSON>Mr. Blehm</PERSON>'s farm produces beneficial insects that devour
crop-destroying bugs. These tiny beasts of prey -- ranging
from ladybugs to praying mantises -- are gaining favor with
farmers as an alternative to costly and environmentally
hazardous pesticides. A smaller sect of farmers raise bugs
that eat weeds.
   Though fledgling, the beneficial-insect industry is
growing fast. It is a small slice of the biological-control
world, but it has grown from nothing five years ago to about
60 firms with combined sales of close to <MONEY>$20 million</MONEY> today.
In that time, <PERSON>Mr. Blehm</PERSON> and others in the field have
discovered what people in other businesses have long known:
New products confuse people.
   These entrepreneurs are learning that any company
introducing a product -- be it a six-legged arthropod or a
laptop computer that transmits data over radio waves -- has
to educate the public on what the product is and how it
works.
   Customers aren't the only ones having trouble figuring out
the firms. Some states have lumped beneficial-insect
companies -- which sell only bugs -- into the same regulatory
category as pesticide dealers.
   Another problem: Some state agencies don't distinguish
between beneficial insects that these firms sell, and
micro-organisms and pathogens, which require <ORGANIZATION>Environmental
Protection Agency</ORGANIZATION> registration. Led in part by the newly
formed <ORGANIZATION>Association of Natural Bio-control Producers</ORGANIZATION>, firms
are rushing to develop model regulations.
   "All we want," says <PERSON>Synthia Penn</PERSON>, president of the group
and her company, <ORGANIZATION>Beneficial Insectary</ORGANIZATION>, "are regulations that
are appropriate to our industry -- specifically, naturally
occurring arthropods. We pose no threat to the public or to
the environment."
   The firms are scrambling to ease the new-product
confusion. They are trying to establish guidelines to assure
the accuracy of advertising claims and to set uniform
standards for raising, shipping and releasing the insects.
   "Biological control has been sort of a novelty in many
areas, but now people are beginning to take it seriously, and
the credibility is being scrutinized," says <PERSON>Glenn Scriven</PERSON>,
owner of <ORGANIZATION>Biotactics Inc.</ORGANIZATION>, a company based in <LOCATION>Grand Terrace</LOCATION>,
<LOCATION>Calif.</LOCATION>, that deals mainly in predatory mites.
   Adds <PERSON>Marjorie Hoy</PERSON>, an entomology professor at the
<ORGANIZATION>University of California</ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION>Berkeley</LOCATION>, "If the industry is
going to grow, it must develop standards and educate
consumers."
   For all its new-product problems, biological control isn't
brand new. In the <DATE>1880s</DATE>, for example, a parasite and a small
lady beetle were imported from <LOCATION>Australia</LOCATION> to attack the
cottony cushion scale, an insect that was devastating
<LOCATION>California</LOCATION>'s citrus industry.
   But practitioners are now much more sophisticated. <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION>
scientists import weedeating and bug-eating insects from
around the world to test. Beneficial insects that aren't
collected in the field are raised in roughly a dozen <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION>
insectaries -- large, environmentally controlled buildings,
similar to greenhouses, lined with racks and trays filled
with insects.
   Some bugs take longer -- sometimes years longer -- than
quick-acting herbicides or pesticides to get results. Some
species are self-perpetuating, and thus are ultimately much
cheaper than chemicals, advocates say. Still others are
native and must be reapplied seasonally.
   <PERSON>Hunter Nadler</PERSON>, a <LOCATION>California</LOCATION> raisin farmer who runs an
80-acre vineyard, buys roughly <MONEY>$6,000</MONEY> of predatory mites,
trichogramma wasps, green lacewings, beetles and ladybird
beetles a year. "It's a lot safer than chemicals, and in some
fields, we've seen increases in production," says a satisfied
<PERSON>Mr. Nadler</PERSON>.
   But not all customers come away as satisfied as <PERSON>Mr.
Nadler</PERSON>. New-product confusion helps some unscrupulous firms
make bogus claims about their insects. Others withhold
information to make a sale -- neglecting to point out, for
example, that parasitic insects attack their pesthosts only
in particular life-cycle phases, such as the egg or larval
stage.
   "People will call a company and say I've got a caterpillar
problem on my lettuce, and some companies ship them insects
no matter what stage the host is in," says <PERSON>Diane Belvanis</PERSON>, a
research entomologist and former employee at a biological
control firm.
   The <ORGANIZATION>Association of Natural Biocontrol Producers</ORGANIZATION> discussed
model industry regulations in a meeting this month with state
officials of <LOCATION>California</LOCATION>, which has been seeking to revamp its
pesticide rules. States such as <LOCATION>North Carolina</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Florida</LOCATION>
also are reviewing ways to regulate the cottage industry.
Meanwhile, a federal effort to coordinate biological control
efforts is under way in the <ORGANIZATION>Agriculture Department</ORGANIZATION>'s newly
formed <ORGANIZATION>National Biological Control Institute</ORGANIZATION>.
   But even as insect companies struggle with the big issues,
they have to grapple with more minute matters. <PERSON>Reed Finfrock</PERSON>,
owner of <ORGANIZATION>Sespe Creek Insectary</ORGANIZATION>, a three-year-old firm in
<LOCATION>Fillmore</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Calif.</LOCATION>, frets over the difficulties of counting the
minuscule creatures he sells. "How," he asks, "do you get
everyone to agree on how to measure 10,000 bugs?"
</TEXT>
