<HEADLINE>  FLY ON THE WALL  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     Relax, <LOCATION>Bunky</LOCATION>, it isn't time to call the exterminator, it's time to get a
good laugh from Flypaper, a new wallpaper designed by <PERSON>Helene Verin.</PERSON>;   
Introduced at the recent <ORGANIZATION>International Contemporary Furniture Fair</ORGANIZATION> in
<LOCATION>Manhattan</LOCATION>, Flypaper is covered with flies, butterflies, ladybugs and beetles.
Not real flies, butterflies, ladybugs and beetles, mind you, but renderings in
gold, against plain backgrounds of white, kraft, forest green or deep blue.;  
 The 2-inch insects are 32 inches apart. Each golden bug seems to alight
alone.;    "Very few wallpapers are hip," says <PERSON>Verin</PERSON>, who lives in <LOCATION>Lenox</LOCATION>,
<LOCATION>Mass.</LOCATION> "Most are those all-over rose patterns with vines, and they don't appeal
to me.";    Flypaper is hand-printed with water-based inks at <PERSON>Verin</PERSON>'s company,
<PERSON>Fern I. Tchur</PERSON>. A roll 5 yards long and 30 inches wide sells for <MONEY>$54</MONEY>.
Information: (413) 637-4444.  </TEXT>
