<DATELINE>OCEAN CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Never mind that the sky was filled with
gray clouds. <PERSON>Martin Z. Mollusk</PERSON> saw his shadow on <DATE>Thursday</DATE>, which
means <DATE>summer</DATE> will arrive a week early.
   The hermit crab performs an annual ritual similar in spirit to
that of <LOCATION>Pennsylvania</LOCATION>'s Punxsutawney <PERSON>Phil</PERSON>, who is said to herald six
more weeks of winter whenever he sees his shadow on <ORGANIZATION>Groundhog Day</ORGANIZATION>.
   Tracy French, <LOCATION>Miss Ocean City</LOCATION>, carried the crustacean mascot to
the beach on a tiny decorated throne. To symbolize <ORGANIZATION>Ocean City</ORGANIZATION>'s
commitment to clean beaches, the throne was set upon a container of
recyclable materials such as aluminum cans and glass bottles.
   With toddlers performing a hula around him and some devoted fans
and curious onlookers standing nearby, <PERSON>Martin</PERSON> crept out of his
shell and saw his shadow _ or so says <PERSON>Mark Soifer</PERSON>, the city's
imaginative public relations director.
   ``It was overcast, so no one thought he would see his shadow,''
<PERSON>Soifer</PERSON> said. ``But trust me _ there was an itsy-bitsy, teeny-weeny
area of sun that came through.''
   <PERSON>Soifer</PERSON> said the omen that <DATE>summer</DATE> will arrive a week ahead of its
normal <DATE>June 21</DATE> date was authenticated by Gus the Amazing Weather
Dog, another <ORGANIZATION>Ocean City</ORGANIZATION> mascot. The dachshund also performs an
annual ritual. He buries <ORGANIZATION>Martin</ORGANIZATION> immediately after the event.
   Martin, however, was again rescued and returned to his ``heated
solarium,'' an aquarium tank in <PERSON>Soifer</PERSON>'s office, until next year.
</TEXT>
