<DESCRIPT>  INSECT; ASSAULT; CHANGE; CHEMICAL; POISON; FRUIT; VEGETABLE  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  There may be a silver lining in the clouds of pesticide-resistant poinsettia
whiteflies infesting the Imperial Valley, which grows a large portion of
America's winter produce.;   While farmers have laid off more than 1,500
workers and figure to lose about $200 million before the winter growing season
ends, entomologists report progress toward finding a remedy.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  California News  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  BENEFITS OF THE WHITEFLY
GROWERS LIKELY TO REDUCE USE OF CHEMICALS ON
FRUITS, VEGETABLES  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     They say the end result could be fruits and vegetables sprayed with fewer
pesticides.;   "The silver lining here is that we could end up with healthier
crops," said <PERSON>Kevin Heinz</PERSON>, a research entomologist at the <ORGANIZATION>University of
California</ORGANIZATION>, Davis.;   But consumers will feel a price- and supply-pinch all
winter because of the infestation, which has already seen thick clouds of tiny
bugs all but denude markets of seasonal cantaloupes.;   Other produce also has
been ravaged, with prices for head lettuce ranging as high as <MONEY>$1.59</MONEY> at some
markets before dropping to just under <MONEY>$1</MONEY> this week.;   Altogether, the bugs
attack about 500 different plants.;   <ORGANIZATION>Heinz</ORGANIZATION>, one of several scientists working
to find a natural predator to keep the whitefly population under control, says
a small ladybug-like beetle now appears to be the most promising possible
future answer. In laboratory tests, the beetle feasts on poinsettia whiteflies
and their larvae, which have resisted extermination by chemical pesticides and
other predators.;   "Based on all the evidence, the beetle is very promising,"
<PERSON>Heinz</PERSON> said. "But we would have to test it large-scale before I would recommend
a large-scale purchase or massive breeding. I would rather not see farmers
spend <MONEY>millions of dollars</MONEY> to acquire large numbers of these beetles until
we've tested it more.";   If farmers are forced to control the whitefly with
large releases of beetles, they'll have to use fewer of the synthetic
organophosphates and other chemicals that they've used to keep insects under
control in the past. Most insecticides would kill the predator along with
adult whiteflies, but they have not been effective in killing whitefly
larvae.;   If the beetle doesn't prove an effective whitefly fighter,
consumers may see big changes in the future mix of winter produce available in
supermarkets.;   "There aren't a lot of other resources where we can get
iceberg head lettuce," said <PERSON>Judi Decker</PERSON>, an executive of <ORGANIZATION>Lucky Stores</ORGANIZATION>, a
428-market <LOCATION>California</LOCATION> chain.;   It was the precise mix of <ORGANIZATION>Imperial Valley</ORGANIZATION>
crops and the order in which they were planted this year that allowed the
proliferation of the poinsettia whitefly, a variety that was new to <LOCATION>California</LOCATION>
and probably migrated aboard plants shipped in from other <LOCATION>Sun Belt states.</LOCATION>;  
"The hosts this year were an ideal combination," said <PERSON>Keith Mayberry</PERSON>, a farm
adviser at the <ORGANIZATION>University of California Cooperative Extension</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Holtville</LOCATION>.
"We had cotton maturing in the <DATE>spring</DATE>, followed by melons and then cauliflower
and broccoli. That was a routine crop pattern in the past.";   All those crops
proved ideal fodder for the whiteflies, which lay their eggs on the underside
of leaves. The larvae kill their hosts by sucking sap from the leaves.;  
"It's not that we can't grow crops even with whiteflies around," said
<PERSON>Mayberry</PERSON>. "But we may have to terminate crops early if we see they're going to
fail.";   He said farmers in the nearby <LOCATION>Yuma</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Ariz.</LOCATION>, area suffered less than
one-tenth as much damage as <ORGANIZATION>Imperial Valley</ORGANIZATION> because they plant a different
crop mix.  </TEXT>
