<LP>
   A natural insecticide derived from an Asian mahogany tree
will soon give consumers an alternative to the synthetic bug
killers that now dominate the lawn care and home gardening
markets.
   The product, developed by W.R. Grace &amp; Co. and to be
distributed by Ringer Corp., will be introduced early next
year. It is intended to challenge such popular synthetic
pesticides as diazinon, malathion and carbaryl, all of which
are toxic to humans and many animals.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The seed extract is the latest example of a growing array
of pest-control technologies that rely on biological
mechanisms instead of manufactured chemicals. As more pests
develop resistance to traditional synthetics, and more
consumers become concerned about pesticide health risks, many
chemical makers are accelerating efforts to produce natural
alternatives.
   The extract, known as azadirachtin, comes from seeds of
the neem tree, a tropical mahogany. The tree can't grow in
most <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> climates, but flourishes in many parts of <LOCATION>south
Asia</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Africa</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Australia</LOCATION>. For centuries, farmers in <LOCATION>India</LOCATION>
have used neem seeds to repel insects in grain storage bins.
   The Grace-Ringer alliance could set the stage for a fierce
marketing battle. Synthetic insecticides generate <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> sales
of more than <MONEY>$1 billion</MONEY> a year. In <DATE>1990</DATE>, more than <MONEY>30 million
pounds</MONEY> of insecticides were applied to residential gardens
and lawns.
   Stakes are high for the makers of these products.
Diazinon, an organophosphate, is the most widely used lawn
and garden pesticide in <LOCATION>America</LOCATION>. It is made by <ORGANIZATION>Ciba Geigy
Corp.</ORGANIZATION> and marketed in the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> by <ORGANIZATION>Chevron Corp.</ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION>Ortho</ORGANIZATION> unit.
<ORGANIZATION>American Cyanamid Co.</ORGANIZATION> makes malathion, another
organophosphate. The most popular brand of carbaryl, called
<PERSON>Sevin</PERSON>, is made by <ORGANIZATION>Rhone-Poulenc S.A.</ORGANIZATION> Organophosphates and
carbaryls kill by attacking the nervous system.
   In contrast, azadirachtin represents a new class of
insecticide that employs a different mechanism. When the
extract is ingested, the insect generally stops eating within
a day. The extract disrupts hormonal changes in the insect
larva, causing death during molting. Jow-Lih Su, a commercial
development specialist for <ORGANIZATION>Grace</ORGANIZATION>, said the extract's
complicated molecule makes it difficult for insects to
develop resistance.
   Greenhouse and field tests have shown that azadirachtin
liquid spray, applied to plant leaves, controls about 170
types of insect pests, including beetles, caterpillars, fruit
flies, crickets, locusts, aphids, weevils, gypsy moths and
mosquitoes.
   Grace researchers found that honey bees and other
beneficial insects that interact with plants only as adults
aren't affected by the product. Neither are earthworms, which
don't molt or eat leaves. Other independent tests indicate
that the product isn't toxic to birds or mammals, including
humans. Ringer officials say the product is safe for contact
by gardeners as soon as it dries, and residues degrade within
a few days.
   Grace, which spent about four years developing the
product, will sell a patented concentrate of the insecticide
to the professional horticultural market under the trade name
Margosan-O. <PERSON>Peter Boer</PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION>Grace</ORGANIZATION>'s executive vice president and
chief technical officer, said the <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> company also sees
potential applications for a variety of food crops, turf and
forests.
   Ringer, based in <LOCATION>Minneapolis</LOCATION>, will offer the product to
home gardeners as Neem starting with its <DATE>spring 1992</DATE>
mail-order catalog and the following year through retailers.
<PERSON>Fred Hundt</PERSON>, Ringer's marketing vice president, said sales
soon could match the company's total volume of about <MONEY>$10
million</MONEY> a year. Moreover, the product may have strong appeal
for organic growers and home gardeners because it leaves no
toxic residue.
   But the relatively short residual effect may make it
necessary to repeat applications several times in a growing
season. Some gardeners who are accustomed to the strong,
immediate "knockdown" effectiveness of synthetic pesticides
may be annoyed by the delayed impact of Neem.
</TEXT>
