<DESCRIPT>  HOUSING; INSECT  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  MOST people remember old homes by their pleasantries: sunlight streaming
through a kitchen window, a back yard's verdant expanse, the neighborhood
peace. I remember my abodes by the bugs that infested them. You name it, I've
battled it: baby Boston and Texas-size cockroaches, crickets of all
proportions, Seattle bees, Santa Ana's giant flying (or gliding, as
entomologists might say) water bugs. By comparison, my latest problem seems
innocuous: Northern California's nocturnal moths. (hbox) Most nights I come
home to find six or eight of these black dusty creatures flattened against my
living room walls, like smirking sentries from some odd underworld bent on
destroying all hope for a blissful, bug-free peace. (hbox) I guess I should
have seen the signs that first fall after college, when I met one of my
prospective housemates, a Harvard law student, for a pre-rental "interview." I
don't remember his name, but he was short and bearded, wore a navy blue down
jacket, had spent the summer working for a San Francisco law firm and seemed
pleasant enough. But his first question was curious. (hbox) "Do you like
bugs?" he asked. He wanted to know whether I liked bugs? Cockroaches, to be
exact. (hbox) "Oh, yeah, sure, live and let live," I said. After all, this guy
held the keys to an affordable apartment within walking distance of Harvard
Square. (hbox) As it turned out, this lawyer-to-be loved bugs. In fact, he
reveled in them. He slept on a futon on the floor in the bedroom closest to
the kitchen -- just to be near them. Sometimes, late at night, they crawled
right up to him and he liked that, he said. This made my stomach turn. And,
looking back, it also marked the end of my carefree, bug-free existence. From
here on out it was me against all manner of them. (hbox) Battling bugs was new
to me, but it has not been what I would call a life-enhancing experience.
(hbox) Thanks to clean suburban living, I enjoyed a relatively bug-free
childhood. I grew up in a Middle Atlantic state where the mosquitoes weren't
bad, bees never stung me and fireflies were something to admire from the
safety of a white concrete patio. If I saw a spider, I simply yelled, "DADDY!"
and then stuck around just long enough to point out the offending critter and
give a good shudder, before getting on with my day.;    Now, I will admit to a
certain fondness for some backyard insects (ladybugs, for their brilliant
beauty) and I will testify to the fact that my friends and I spent a period of
time enthralled by praying mantises. And, yes, when the 17-year cicadas
descended upon our pristine world, we collected their wings. They, after all,
were exotic.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Home  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  BATTLING BUGS
A VETERAN CRITTER CRUNCHER TAKES UP FIGHT
AGAINST LATEST FLYING, SMIRKING INVADER  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Cover Story
See related stories pages 1E and 3E of this section.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     But all this gentle interaction with the world of bugs led to my adult
aversion to all minute beings that creep, crawl or fly -- indoors. My college
education didn't prepare me for the horrors of a pest-ridden post-graduate
life.;    It's not as if I wasn't careful. I never rented a place where
cobwebs covered the window sills or spiders stared out from the bedspreads,
though, believe me, I saw my share. I never kept open packages of food in the
cabinets. And as for stashing flour, the refrigerator's always been the place
for me.;    New home, new bugs;  No, these pests were feline in their
attachment to my various homes. I might hardly have time to unpack before some
new job called me to another state. But they had already spread their antennae
-- or wings -- into every crack and crevice.;    Even from the perspective of
time and empty Raid cans, it is hard to decide which were worse: <LOCATION>Santa Ana</LOCATION>'s
flying water bugs or <LOCATION>Southern Maryland</LOCATION>'s chirping crickets. The water bugs
(water bug, an entomologist confirms, is simply a euphemism for cockroach,
though my apartment manager insisted the two were unrelated) raised their ugly
antennae (and wings) in my dishwasher, on my bed and on a painting of a palm
tree hanging innocently in a hallway. They also scurried about after dark on
both my sun decks.;    Once, when my friend <PERSON>Steve</PERSON> was visiting from <LOCATION>Alaska</LOCATION>, I
enlisted his help in nabbing a particularly large water bug that was evading
capture by hiding behind the toilet. The water bug took a flying leap into a
nightshirt hanging on the bathroom towel rack, and the best <PERSON>Steve</PERSON> could do was
knock both bug and nightshirt into a grocery sack -- with the help of a stick.
Even this guy just in from the last frontier couldn't bring himself to touch a
water bug.;    Long night of chirps;  Still, the crickets were probably worse.
These were in <LOCATION>Huntingtown</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Md.</LOCATION>, on the western shore of the <LOCATION>Chesapeake Bay</LOCATION>, an
area known as <ORGANIZATION>Tobacco Country</ORGANIZATION>. It was also, as I soon learned, home to an
all-night shrieking, Mexican-jumping-bean variety of black cricket. I lived in
a converted antique shop on a low hill just off Route 4, close enough to smell
the motorcycle exhaust and close enough to the local fire station to keep tabs
on every emergency run. My landlords told me the molding around the bathroom
floor wasn't yet complete, but I didn't think much of it -- until <DATE>spring</DATE>
arrived, and with it, the crickets.;    At first they were just tiny, silent
things that hopped about the bathroom floor. They were easy to nab. But then
they started growing and multiplying and sending forth chirps at all hours of
the <TIME>night</TIME>. And they didn't confine themselves to the bathroom. I would come
home late at night to find packs of them jumping outside my front door. They
were also jumping inside. And soon they lodged themselves in my bedroom walls
and chirped the night away. I sprayed. I smashed them with rolled newspapers.
I knocked them senseless with an old brown shoe. I had the landlords fix the
molding. Nothing helped. Did I care that crickets are an ancient symbol of
good fortune? No. I moved.;    Which brings me to my current problem: those
nocturnal moths. These are in the cozy condo I recently rented below the
<LOCATION>Saratoga</LOCATION> foothills. Just a short walk to town, nestled in redwoods and near a
real running stream, it's a rather pleasant place. The only annoyances had
been the neighbors' drifting cigarette smoke and a wandering pet that one
morning left a pile of fish-stinking vomit in the carport.;    Night of the
moths;  But then came the moths. When I first visited the apartment, in broad
daylight, they were nowhere to be seen. But what pests ever rear their ugly
heads when a landlord is present? As soon as I moved in, they were there to
taunt me. And a well-worn flyswatter stashed behind the kitchen door confirmed
their persistence.;    So out came my trusty cedar-scented moth spray. And out
came my sachets of herbal moth repellent. Still, each night I came home and
smashed more moths.;    To learn more about these dark and silent creatures, I
called the <ORGANIZATION>University of California Cooperative Extension Service</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Santa
Clara</LOCATION>. "A moth," the receptionist said, searching through her pamphlets.
"That's not like a silverfish or a firebrat is it?";    I don't think so.
Silverfish (and firebrats) tend to slither around in the bathtub, eat paper
and leave behind yellow stains. These are all things I recently learned from a
page of information received from <PERSON>Bill Ng</PERSON>, the extension service's master
gardener.;    Ng also gave me a copy of a pamphlet called "Clothes Moths and
Carpet Beetles," from which I learned that my moths are not clothes moths, but
stored-food moths. I had Leaflet 2524; I needed Leaflet 2711.;    The next
morning I went to the <LOCATION>Saratoga</LOCATION> library to look for it. "You mean food moths,
the ones that fly around your kitchen?" librarian <PERSON>Barbara Hall</PERSON> asked with a
knowing smile. "The only way I know to get rid of them is to move.";    <PERSON>Hall</PERSON>,
it seems, is a food-moth veteran. Her latest batch of moths infested an
unopened bag of sliced almonds, but once they came in with the dog food and
they adore cold cereal, she says. "The cat loves to catch them," she adds.;   
She hasn't seen any in a while, "but they'll get there eventually. I keep
expecting them. As I say, it seems fairly hopeless.";    How can a problem as
small and silent as a moth be hopeless? I drove to <ORGANIZATION>Ng</ORGANIZATION>'s office for Leaflet
2711, "Common Pantry Pests and Their Control." My moths, it seems, are Indian
meal moths, which "breed in spilled food on shelves and in the cracks and
crevices in every kitchen. . . . Most home infestations result from
carelessness in maintaining clean cupboards or from having open packages
around for long periods of time.";    And herein lay the answer.;    My
apartment's previous tenants (who, I am sad to report, are in the food
business), had spilled flour on the top shelves of both sets of kitchen
cabinets. I spent <DATE>several hours one weekend</DATE> cleaning out one side of this
mess. It was so unpleasant that I couldn't even bring myself to peek into the
other side.;    That night I went home to look. And there it was: more spilled
flour and a scattering of dead moths. The landlords say they will come and
clean it.;    And if the moths still don't go away? There's always <PERSON>Barbara
Hall</PERSON>'s advice: Pack my bags and move.;    Ah, but who can predict what new
pest might lie on this renter's horizon?  </TEXT>
