<HEAD>Exotic Pests Threaten Farm Economy</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE V. BIGELOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EL MONTE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lured like other visitors to <LOCATION>California</LOCATION>
by the warm climate, record numbers of exotic insects are invading
<LOCATION>Los Angeles County</LOCATION> and posing an unprecedented threat to the state's
<MONEY>$16 billion</MONEY> a year farm economy.
   As of <DATE>July</DATE>, 1,185 potentially harmful pests have appeared in
<LOCATION>California</LOCATION>, including fruit flies and gypsy moths, fire ants,
Russian wheat aphids, Japanese beetles, mealy bugs and scales.
   ``We are being literally swamped,'' said <PERSON>Rosser W. Garrison</PERSON>, a
county entomologist who supplied the statistics. ``The variety of
insects is increasing, and the sheer number is increasing.''
   Besides the climate, <LOCATION>Los Angeles</LOCATION> has become a magnet for imported
insects because of the ease of international travel. More than 3.7
million foreigners passed through <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> Customs at <LOCATION>Los Angeles
International Airport</LOCATION> last year, and at least some presumably
slipped fresh fruit and vegetables past inspectors, officials said.
   One of the new pests, the ash whitefly, already has reached
epidemic proportions in <LOCATION>Southern California</LOCATION> and is racing for the
state's agricultural heartland _ the <LOCATION>San Joaquin Valley</LOCATION> in <LOCATION>central
California</LOCATION>.
   The city, a hub for commerce with <LOCATION>Asia</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>South America</LOCATION>, boasts
a burgeoning immigrant population with a taste for fruits and
vegetables from their native countries.
   ``They have friends and family who are sending them a taste of
home,'' said <PERSON>Robert G. Atkins</PERSON>, a deputy county agricultural
commissioner.
   <PERSON>Atkins</PERSON> said that although <LOCATION>Los Angeles County</LOCATION>'s farm production is
negligible, the county acts as the entry for pests to the rest of
the state _ the nation's leading agricultural producer.
   He noted that <LOCATION>California</LOCATION>'s belated response to a <LOCATION>Mediterranean</LOCATION>
fruit fly infestation drew widespread publicity nine years ago,
eventually costing the state <MONEY>$100 million</MONEY> to exterminate and farmers
<MONEY>$100 million</MONEY> in losses. But similar invasions lately have become
almost mundane.
   ``I hate to stress that, because I don't want people to believe
that the bug is any less dangerous,'' <PERSON>Atkins</PERSON> said.
   Nevertheless, three medfly infestations have occurred in the
county within the <DATE>last 12 months</DATE>, each costing roughly <MONEY>$1 million</MONEY> to
eradicate and each drawing comparatively scant public attention.
   The county's budget for plant quarantine last year was more than
<MONEY>$784,000</MONEY>, an almost <PERCENT>54 percent</PERCENT> increase over <DATE>fiscal year 1977-78</DATE>,
officials said.
   Treatment methods vary for different types of fruit flies, but
early detection is a fundamental strategy, made possible by checking
more than 160,000 baited traps set throughout the state.
   ``It's almost like battling forest fires,'' <PERSON>Garrison</PERSON> said. ``It's
a lot easier to put it out as soon as it gets started.''
   Discoveries of less notorious pests are charted each month by
Garrison, whose microscopic scrutiny detected five new types of
insects in the county <DATE>last year</DATE> and three so far this year.
   Although agriculture officials have established methods of
dealing with fruit fly infestations, other kinds of insects can be
neither readily identified nor exterminated.
   One of the most ruinous new pests, the ash whitefly, apparently
hitchhiked to the suburban <LOCATION>San Fernando Valley</LOCATION> from <LOCATION>Europe</LOCATION> or the
<LOCATION>Middle East</LOCATION>. It has no natural enemies in <LOCATION>California</LOCATION> and its numbers
are exploding.
   ``It is totally out of control,'' <PERSON>Atkins</PERSON> said. ``The only thing
limiting the population is the number of trees they have to eat. It
is expanding as fast as it can, and chemical (pesticide) control is
just totally not feasible.''
   Although fruit flies, which lay their eggs in hundreds of fruits
and vegetables, are like a cancer, <PERSON>Atkins</PERSON> said the ash whitefly acts
more like a low-grade virus. It attaches itself to the underside of
leaves and slowly sucks the life out of trees.
   At first, agriculture officials were unconcerned because they
believed the tiny new invader only attacked ornamental trees like
the ash, <PERSON>Atkins</PERSON> said.
   But they later discovered the ash whitefly thrives in dozens of
varieties of trees, including olive, pear, apple and peach trees.
   To combat the ash whitefly, agriculture officials have dispatched
an entomologist to <LOCATION>France</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Italy</LOCATION> to collect several varieties of
<LOCATION>Encarsia</LOCATION>, pinhead-sized wasps that are the insect's natural enemy.
   If tests prove successful, millions of the tiny wasps could be
released come <DATE>winter</DATE>, though it probably will be years before the
wasps can significantly reduce the ash whitefly population.
</TEXT>
