<DESCRIPT>  ENVIRONMENT; CHEMICAL; INSECT; GARDEN  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  PEST control in the '90s is focusing so strongly on environmentally sound
methods that scientists are working overtime trying to unlock the secrets of
chemicals called pheromones.;    That may well be where the greatest strides
in ecologically safe pest control are realized.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Garden  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  ON THE TRAIL OF A BUG-SCENTED, PEST-FREE
GARDEN  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     Pheromones are insect sex attractants. Adult females of each species use
these powerful scents to lure males when they're ready to mate.;    The insect
world is truly a jungle. Thousands of different kinds of insects inhabit each
acre of ground. Pheromones serve as "identification cards," separating the
beetles from the moths. Insects use pheromones to keep order among the
species.;    While pheromones might be likened superficially to perfumes,
they're much more complex than that. Each one is different. If it weren't,
male beetles of one species, for example, would try to mate with receptive
female beetles of another. They don't.;    Deciphering a pheromone's intricate
chemical code is the first step in reproducing that chemical synthetically.
Already about 40 synthetic pheromones are helping to control some very
pernicious pests.;    Pheromones don't control pest populations in the
traditional sense. Traps, usually coated with a sticky substance, are
outfitted with a vial containing the pheromone, then hung in the field.;    As
the scent is released, males fly toward a trap in hopes of mating with the
"female" inside. Those amorous few are captured and die; no pesticide is
involved.;    There are several reasons why pheromone traps must be considered
just one weapon in our pest control arsenal. The most important is that
pheromone traps do not eliminate females, and females are the ones that lay
eggs.;    Can't catch all;  Also, pheromone traps can't capture enough of the
available males to prevent successful mating. Even if <PERCENT>80 percent</PERCENT> were
captured, the remainder of the males could, in most species, fertilize all the
females.;    Even though pheromone traps do not provide significant insect
population reduction, they are extremely effective for monitoring pest
populations.;    As monitoring devices, pheromone traps primarily enable
growers to pinpoint the appropriate time to spray for a pest, resulting in
more efficient control with fewer sprays.;    Instead of covering apple trees
with as many as 18 pesticide sprays per season, pheromone traps have reduced
that number to two or three for some insects. Research continues to fine-tune
the system and make the apparatus available to orchardists.;    Spray
schedules adjusted;    A pheromone study throughout <LOCATION>Pennsylvania</LOCATION> several years
ago determined that information being disseminated about the rhododendron
borer was correct. Trapping showed borer emergence to be two to three weeks
later than previously suspected. Spray schedules were adjusted accordingly
with better results.;    In addition to rhododendron borer and gypsy moth,
synthetic pheromones have been developed for bagworm, corn earworm, European
corn borer, grape berry moth, lesser peach-tree borer, cabbage looper, black
cutworm, dogwood borer and Oriental fruit moth. All are serious agricultural
or landscape pests.;    Promising developments in pheromone research are
leading entomologists in the direction of a process called mating disruption.
When an area is saturated with pheromone scents, males are so confused they're
unable to locate receptive females.;    Cost still lower;    Much more of the
pheromone is required to disrupt mating than is used in trapping, but costs
are still lower than traditional control methods and fewer pesticides are
needed.;    Mating disruption has significantly reduced populations of grape
berry moths in vineyards and Oriental fruit moths on peaches. Remarkably,
mating disruption has achieved the same level of control as three pesticide
sprays for the lesser peachtree borer in <LOCATION>California</LOCATION>. The lesser peachtree
borer is also a major problem on peaches in the Northeast.;    Someday
pheromone trapping and mating disruption techniques will be pest control
methods not only available to home gardeners, but taken for granted.  </TEXT>
