<CAPTION>  Photo, drawing; PHOTO: Eucalyptus trees have recently been infested with a
beetle that has no natural enemies in California.; DRAWING: (Insect) (Color)  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  INSECT; WAR  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  SCIENTISTS in two Bay Area counties started a quiet war last week. The
battlegrounds are ash trees, the soldiers are thousands of insects and the
generals are arborists and entomologists.;    The war began with the release
in Alameda and Santa Clara counties of stingless mini-wasps, or Encarsia
wasps, which attack ash whiteflies. Here's how it works: The mini-wasp, which,
like the whitefly, is the size of a pinhead, lays its eggs in the scales of
young whiteflies. As the wasp matures, it feeds on the whitefly and kills it.;
   The parasite was imported by scientists at the University of California,
Riverside, from Israel, home of the ash tree. Mini-wasps are natural parasites
of the whitefly and control their populations in Israel and other countries
where the trees are native.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Garden  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  IN BUG WARS, PESTS PROVE KEY DEFENSE  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     When whiteflies infested <LOCATION>California</LOCATION> in the late <DATE>1980s</DATE>, probably
accidentally brought in on infected trees, they thrived because they had no
natural enemies here, said <PERSON>Mark Beaudoin</PERSON>, city arborist for <LOCATION>San Jose.</LOCATION>;   
Efforts to control the whitefly through spraying are useless because the
insects are so prolific, he said. "We'd have to spray every seven days." And
the problem is so widespread that the insects killed by the insecticide would
soon be replaced by others from nearby trees.;    Controlling the whitefly has
been a high priority in the state, <PERSON>Beaudoin</PERSON> said, because in addition to ash
trees, the pest attacks cash crops such as pear and citrus trees and landscape
plants.;    With state funding, the UC-Riverside scientists imported the
mini-wasps and other natural parasites for the whitefly and studied them to
determine which would be most likely to thrive in <LOCATION>California</LOCATION>. Last year they
released the chosen mini-wasp in six <LOCATION>Southern California</LOCATION> counties where
whitefly infestations were most intense.;    "The program was very
successful," said <PERSON>Timothy Paine</PERSON>, assistant professor of entomology at
UC-Riverside. The scientists measured the success by releasing the parasite at
five sites and then monitoring them along with five similar sites that didn't
receive the mini-wasps. A graduate student conducting the study found that in
the areas where the parasite was released, the populations of adult and
immature whiteflies "took a huge nose dive. They dropped to very low levels,"
<PERSON>Paine</PERSON> said. In the sites where no parasites were released, whiteflies
flourished.;    Follow-up studies showed that the whitefly populations
remained low, <PERSON>Paine</PERSON> said. "And the parasite is such a good colonizer that as
the whiteflies moved, so did the parasite," he said.;    The success in
<LOCATION>Southern California</LOCATION> encouraged other counties to try the mini-wasp warriors,
<PERSON>Beaudoin</PERSON> says. "We were losing the battle (against the whitefly) with
traditional methods.";    To introduce the mini-wasp to the <LOCATION>South Bay</LOCATION>, the
<ORGANIZATION>Santa Clara County Department of Agriculture</ORGANIZATION> chose five sites -- in <LOCATION>San Jose</LOCATION>,
<LOCATION>Saratoga</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Santa Clara</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Los Gatos</LOCATION> -- to serve as nurseries for the parasite,
said agriculture biologist <PERSON>Stan Maggi.</PERSON>;    The mini-wasps, which were raised
in a laboratory in <LOCATION>Sacramento</LOCATION>, were released onto infested ash trees. "We
don't expect results this year," <PERSON>Maggi</PERSON> said. "Any tree infected has hundreds
of thousands of whiteflies. It's a long-term project.";    Importing insects
to control pests isn't new. Perhaps the most well-publicized effort was the
release of sterile male <LOCATION>Mediterranean</LOCATION> fruit flies to control those insects, a
program that has been fairly successful <PERSON>Beaudoin</PERSON> said.;    Another effort was
undertaken in the mid-1970s to control aphids on linden trees. Aphids, which
feed on plant sap of several species of trees, secrete honeydew that drops
from the trees, making a sticky mess.;    "The aphids don't harm the tree,"
said <PERSON>Bob Zuparko</PERSON>, a graduate student at <ORGANIZATION>UC-Berkeley's Division of Biological
Control</ORGANIZATION> who is studying the linden tree aphid and its parasite for his
doctoral dissertation.;    The honeydew, however, is a nuisance. Zuparko
worked with the group that released the linden tree aphid parasites, a
mini-wasp called Trioxys Curvicaubus, in <LOCATION>San Jose</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Berkeley.</LOCATION>;    "The
parasite was released in <DATE>1978</DATE>, and the aphid population went way down,"
<PERSON>Zuparko</PERSON> said. His current study however, reveals that the efforts have not
been a complete success. "The populations are low, but there is still
honeydew," he said.;    Linden tree aphids are not a high priority in <LOCATION>San
Jose</LOCATION>, because the city has very few mature linden trees and the trees need to
develop before aphids attack, <PERSON>Zuparko</PERSON> said. Most of the city's lindens are on
one street in <ORGANIZATION>Willow Glen</ORGANIZATION>, with a few single lindens in other neighborhoods.; 
  Young lindens, however, were planted along the light rail line,
significantly increasing the city's linden tree population.;    The linden
tree parasite has made its own effort to branch out. A survey by <PERSON>Zuparko</PERSON> shows
that the mini-wasp has spread from <LOCATION>Berkeley</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>San Jose</LOCATION> all around the <LOCATION>Bay</LOCATION>,
but has not crossed any hills. As part of his work, <PERSON>Zuparko</PERSON> plans to introduce
the mini-wasp to another area infested with linden tree aphids to further
study how the parasite works.;    Although linden tree aphids feast on only
that tree, other types of aphids attack other trees. Scientists brought in a
mini-wasp to control the tulip tree aphid with little success, said <PERSON>Beaudoin</PERSON>,
who manages about 250,000 street trees for the city of <LOCATION>San Jose.</LOCATION>;    One
effort that appears to be a failure was a parasite released to control the elm
leaf beetle. The parasite "was whipped out before it could get established,"
<PERSON>Beaudoin</PERSON> said. Scientists don't know for sure what killed the parasite, but it
could have been a fungus, disease or organism that prevented the predator from
flourishing. "We're messing with a complex system here," <PERSON>Beaudoin</PERSON> said.;   
Yet another tree that has fallen victim to recently imported insects is the
eucalyptus. "It used to be a pest-free plant, but now we have a pest,"
<PERSON>Beaudoin</PERSON> said. The eucalyptus long-horn beetle came from <LOCATION>Australia</LOCATION>, home of
the eucalyptus tree. The beetle found its way to <LOCATION>California</LOCATION> on eucalyptus wood
palates used to carry goods imported from Australia.;    Scientists hoping to
control the beetle must travel to <LOCATION>Australia</LOCATION> to study the insect and its
natural enemies, and then bring back predators and determine if they can
survive in <LOCATION>California</LOCATION>. If and when this happens depends on financial support
for the program, <PERSON>Beaudoin</PERSON> said. While the cash-crop attacking whitefly drew
attention and funds from the state, no one gets as excited about the
eucalyptus, he said.  </TEXT>
