<LEADPARA>  LET'S TALK dirty here for a moment. Actually, let's talk "dirt," as in the
stuff plants go into. Look at that picture at the top of the column. Well,
what you don't see is my dark brown plant-killing thumb (scientific name:
plantkillus thumbius). I can kill ivy, bamboo, spider plants, air fern, "chia
pet" grass, etc.;   For example, not too long ago my wife went on a business
trip for a week and left me instructions to "water the spider plants ONLY once
on Wednesday." I did. I poured cool water around the base of each plant (not
on the foliage or whatever you call those ugly leaves), and several weeks
later two of the plants appeared arthritic and eventually died.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Peninsula Extra  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  GARDENERS, HELP! STOP ME BEFORE I DEFOLIATE AGAIN  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Also ran in EX2/1, EX3/2; Comment  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     In a family gift exchange I was given a chia pet. Remember those? The
container is shaped like an animal -- mine was a sheep and was filled with
grass seeds, that germinate and the blades grow out tiny holes and are
supposed to make the chia look like a real animal. Mine looked like a mildewy
wool rug, and then it died.;   WHEN an elderly gentleman moved from his home
across the street, we were given his air fern. It must have been 10 years old.
It turned into something that resembled the stem after you've eaten all the
grapes off it.;   With this background you can see why I'm not a gardener and
why when I was forced to replace a plant for my mom and dad I dreaded the
project. I sought expertise. I was looking for a patient clerk with a
doctorate in <LOCATION>Landscape Plantology</LOCATION>, a recognized master gardener and an
accredited nursery person all rolled into one.;   No such person exists at the
discount garden centers. They may infer that these people exist within the
walls of their plant departments, but finding them can be another story. This
led me to <ORGANIZATION>Yamagami's Nursery</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Cupertino</LOCATION>, because it's been around a long
time and advertises "11 <LOCATION>California</LOCATION> Certified Nurserymen" on staff. I figured
that if we could find one of the "11," I'd find something to stick in a pot.; 
 We were helped by <PERSON>Ron</PERSON>, the garden center's manager. I told him that what we
needed was a plant to stick in a shaded corner, one that didn't require a lot
of care and was about this big by about this tall. Ron immediately started
walking through aisles and aisles of lush looking plants, talking about the
restrictions we were imposing on the selection and showed us some kind of
bamboo and this little-leafed thing called a shrubby yew pine (Podocarpus
maki). We liked it. Then he spotted some ants. "Aphids," he said.;   HE
EXAMINED the plant's leaves and exclaimed that famous medical term "hmmmm." It
seems that the ants were protecting the aphids (tinybugses) from ladybugs
(flyawayhomius). According to <PERSON>Ron</PERSON>, the aphids produce a sweet, sticky goop
that ants either eat or use for something or other, therefore the ants keep
their "goo providers" from being eaten by the ladybugs.;   <PERSON>Ron</PERSON> said that he'd
need to have Mas, an older gentlemen who also said "hmmmm" when told about the
aphids, spray the plant.;   The good news here is that the shrubby yew pine
survived the trip home. Survived being wrestled from its plastic container.
Survived our mixing planter mix with some kind of fertilizer. Survived -- so
far -- in its pot for SEVEN DAYS.;   I think I'm on to something here. I was
just studying my thumb and I notice that it looks a bit different. It could be
turning green.;   No, wait. Wait a minute! I think I've got aphids.  </TEXT>
