<LP>
   Biotech companies that are trying to engineer
insect-killing genes into big commercial crops like cotton,
corn, and potato are getting a worrisome signal from a moth
in Hawaii.
   Plant scientists at several companies including Monsanto
Co., have poured millions of dollars into what appears to be
a successful attempt to take genes from a bacterium called Bt
(for Bacillus thurigiensis) and put them into plants. The
genes produce proteins that kill insects by interfering with
their digestion. Laboratory and greenhouse tests show that a
bug taking a bite out of a plant carrying one of these
bacterial genes will quickly discover it's eaten its last
meal.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The genetic engineering feat is so promising, <ORGANIZATION>Monsanto</ORGANIZATION> has
been conducting field trials of cotton plants incorporating
the Bt gene for two years.
   But a group of entomologists from the <ORGANIZATION>University of Hawaii</ORGANIZATION>
say they have documented cases in Hawaiian watercress fields
in which the diamondback moth, a common pest, has developed
strong resistance to insecticide sprays containing a Bt
toxin. "The results of our study put to rest the notion that
<ORGANIZATION>Bt</ORGANIZATION> will be a permanent solution to our pest problems," said
<PERSON>Bruce Tabashnik</PERSON>, professor of entomology and one of the
researchers, "There was a perception until recently that
insects won't develop resistance to Bt as they have to
chemical pesticides."
   Prof. <PERSON>Tabashnik</PERSON> said the diamondback moth's resistance to
<ORGANIZATION>Bt</ORGANIZATION> should also be seen as "an early warning that other
insects can develop resistance" to other strains of Bt. A
number of companies -- <ORGANIZATION>Monsanto</ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION>Ecogen Inc.</ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION>Du Pont Co.</ORGANIZATION>,
<ORGANIZATION>Calgene Inc.</ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION>Entotech Inc.</ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION>Agracetus</ORGANIZATION>, a subsidiary of <ORGANIZATION>W. R.
Grace &amp; Co.</ORGANIZATION> -- have developed or are currently testing
different strains of the bacterium against such pests as
cottonplant eating caterpillars, corn borers, and potato
beetles.
   Some of these companies expressed concern over the
evidence collected in <LOCATION>Hawaii</LOCATION>, but said it wasn't conclusive.
Also they have already been pursuing strategies that take Bt
resistance into account.
   Some companies are using the Bt-toxin in the form of
sprays, such as the ones used on the fields in <LOCATION>Hawaii</LOCATION>, and
others, like <ORGANIZATION>Monsanto</ORGANIZATION>, are engineering the gene for the toxin
right into the crop.
   <ORGANIZATION>Monsanto</ORGANIZATION> is considering incorporating into the plants more
than one strain of the bacterium. "There is a low probability
that the insect will develop resistance to both at the same
time," said <PERSON>Randy Deaton</PERSON>, a scientist at its plant sciences
unit.
   Chi-Li Liu, who heads the microbiology operation at
<LOCATION>Entotech</LOCATION>, a <LOCATION>Davis</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Calif.</LOCATION>, unit of <ORGANIZATION>Novo Nordisk</ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION>Denmark</LOCATION>,
said her company is closely monitoring the fields where its
Bt-based insecticide sprays are used. "We don't believe that
if Bt pesticides are properly used by farmers insects would
develop resistance," she said. Entotech recommends farmers
rotate Bt-based pesticides with the traditional
chemical-based products and rotating crops.
   But Prof. <PERSON>Tabashnik</PERSON> believes that the evidence of
resistance developed by the diamondback moth is likely to
damp the heavy reliance of companies on Bt for biological
control of pests. He said there have been other convincing
reports of resistance developing in moths in <LOCATION>Florida</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>,
and the <LOCATION>Philippines</LOCATION>. The diamondback moth is a pest of
cabbage, broccoli, watercress, and brussel sprouts, among
other crops.
   It's uncertain how long it takes for an insect to develop
a resistance to the Bt toxins. The Hawaiian fields where
Prof. <PERSON>Tabashnik</PERSON> and his co-researchers found moth resistance
had been using sprays containing Bt from <DATE>1978</DATE> to <DATE>1982</DATE>, and
again from <DATE>1988</DATE> to present.
</TEXT>
