<DESCRIPT>  HOUSING; INSECT; GUIDELINE  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  IN most cases, simple common sense practices are the key to keeping insects in
check. So, if you're pestered by household pests, do a little cleanup work.
And above all, don't be embarrassed. Says William Chaney, entomology farm
adviser for the UC Cooperative Extension Service: "I would stress that this
doesn't indicate poor housekeeping on anyone's part. It's just a matter of
circumstance and chance. It can happen to anyone.";    So enough bug talk.
With warm, bug-filled weather just around the corner, here are some tips to
ensure that your home keeps a low pest profile:  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Home  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  A LITTLE ELBOW GREASE KEEPS PESTS FROM GETTING
THE BEST OF YOU  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  See related stories pages 1E and 3E of this section.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     (box) Keep flour and other foods, even pet foods, in air-tight containers.
Tupperware-style containers are good; plastic bags won't do. Often, moths and
other pests enter a home through an infested store-bought package. So if you
spot worms in a package of food, throw the whole thing out. Don't try to save
part of it, and don't mix a new batch of food into the old. Clean infested
shelves with water and a small amount of Lysol or ammonia.;    (box) Plug
baseboards and areas around sink pipes. Cockroaches love dark, humid places
and are notorious for poking their way through holes around sinks. Also, keep
garbage covered and don't let it accumulate.;    (box) Use caulking around
windows and weatherproof your home with weatherstripping. These measures save
energy -- and create a physical barrier to insects.;    (box) Keep
nectar-bearing plants such as fruit trees, showy flowers and fast-growing
herbaceous plants away from the house perimeter. Ants feed on the sweet
secretions of the aphids that attack these plants. Drought-resistant plants
such as juniper and chaparral are a better choice for house-side landscaping.;
   (box) In clothes closets and drawers, use insect-repelling cedar blocks or
cedar and lavender sachets. Kettle Care of <LOCATION>Kalispell</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Mont.</LOCATION>, sells a sachet
containing a mix of herbs known as insect repellents since Roman times:
lavender, cedar, penny royal and rosemary. The 3-by-5-inch calico sachet (for
use in drawers, closets, chests and kitchens) is <MONEY>$2</MONEY>, plus <MONEY>$1</MONEY> shipping and
handling, from <ORGANIZATION>Kettle Care</ORGANIZATION>, <DATE>1145</DATE> 2nd Ave. E., <LOCATION>Kalispell</LOCATION> 59901; (406)
756-3485.;    If you can't identify a pest, have questions about pest control
or need the expert advice required for dealing with tough critters like
termites and carpet beetles, call the <ORGANIZATION>UC Cooperative Extension Service</ORGANIZATION>: in
<LOCATION>Santa Clara County</LOCATION>, (408) 299-2635 (ask for a master gardener); in <LOCATION>Santa Cruz</LOCATION>,
(408) 425-2591.;    The extension service sells a variety of leaflets that
detail common household pests and their control. Controlling Household
Cockroaches (Leaflet No. 21035), Common Pantry Pests and Their Control (No.
2711), Clothes Moths and Carpet Beetles (No. 2524) and Termites and Other
Wood-Destroying Insects (No. 2537) cost <MONEY>50 cents</MONEY> each. Key to Ants (No. 21344)
costs <MONEY>$2</MONEY> (probably because it includes 14 color photographs, <PERSON>Garrison</PERSON> says).
The booklets are available through extension service offices.  </TEXT>
